Maybe a fisheye lens for a nest box is a bit too much of a good thing.
One never learns from mistakes.
I should have known better, since I already built one with a "normal" lens before.
I will write more about it this weekend as soon as I have installed the second one.
Let's just say that the birds will have a better internet connection than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box that already has a nest is consuming a lot of WLAN data.
It will be a bit more difficult for the other one to go online.
Okay, I hung up the new nest box today. This is what it looks like in its new place in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one is asking: "What exactly is inside?"
At the top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera with a fisheye lens and an IR-LED that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swivel side wall of the nest box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the gray box that is hanging on the side of the nest box is the battery.
When it's charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
I'll call that a feature. This way, the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
That's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and point it downwards into the garden.
Perhaps I will do that if I set up more nest boxes with cameras. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably need that.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It only turned off one hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery didn't charge any further three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or something less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I guess I have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
Generally, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And maybe a battery that is at least theoretically capable of keeping the thing running overnight.
Ah yes, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite overkill.
But I'm already looking for parts at Digikey so that I can build my own board specifically for that.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And it's still offline.
Great.
According to the actual solar panels on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another one or two hours to see what happens – or not.
Still offline.
It's never easy, anyway.
It turned out that on the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger, the 5 V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lighting up.
The ESP did not go online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and it is still offline.
It looks like it is restarting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is just useless. I have now ordered a larger one and hope that it will work.
Take a look at what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and is partially obscured by a tree), that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I turn the device on.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this setup or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought this panel in 2021 and it should supply 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or my multimeter, or the data has been changed.
Good news!
You have changed the data and the ones I have are wrong.
The old one and also the new listing title call it a 12 V 10-W panel.
That's why I never delete old emails.
Oh look! The thing went back online about an hour ago, for about half a minute.
Perhaps the panel just charged the battery long enough for 38 seconds of runtime. It only took a bit more than two hours for that.
Guess what: It's cloudy today. Therefore, I'm not sure if the (probably broken) solar panel will manage to generate enough power at all.
Let's just wait.
Update: I have installed the new panel and now it seems to be working.
It could still go offline as soon as the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Fun fact: I use the Ping integration in Home Assistant to see if it's online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but also not wildly bad.
